# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: akpeteshie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abẹokuta lies in fertile country of wooded savanna, the surface of which is broken by masses of grey granite.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] It spreads over an extensive area, being surrounded by mud walls 29 km (18 mi) in extent.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Palm oil, lumber, natural rubber, yams, rice, cassava, maize, cotton, fruits, and shea butter are the chief articles of trade.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] It is a key export location for cocoa, palm products, fruits, and kola nuts.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Both rice and cotton were introduced by the missionaries in the 1850s and have become integral parts of the economy, along with the dye indigo.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abeokuta lies below the Olumo Rock, home to several caves and shrines.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The city depends on the Oyan River Dam for its water supply, which is not always dependable.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The dam is situated in the Abeokuta North local government area of Ogun State in the West of Nigeria, about 20 km northwest of the state capital Abeokuta.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The dam crosses the Oyan River, a tributary of the Ogun River.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abeokuta is the headquarters of the Ogun-Oshun River Basin Development Authority, which is responsible for development of land and water resources for Lagos, Ogun, and Oyo states.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Included in its development programme are irrigation, food-processing, and electrification.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Local industries include but are not limited to fruit canning plants, plastics, breweries, sawmills, and an aluminum products factory.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] South of town are the Aro granite quarries.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] An account suggests that the early Abeokuta settlements were established by Yoruba migrants from various places within Yoruba land.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Orile Egba continued to exist until its destruction during the Yoruba Civil Wars of the 19th century.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] As a result, many of the leading families of the Egba claim descent from the Eso Ikoyis today.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abeokuta was founded as a replacement for Orile Egba in around 1830 by the Egbas after the collapse of the Oyo empire during the civil war.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The city was founded because of its strong defensive physical position by refugees trying to protect themselves against slave raiders from Dahomey, who were trying to benefit from the war.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Owu-focused account states that in 1817, the Oyo Empire dissolved into civil war.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Refugees displaced by the collapse of Oyo joined with the Ijebu in their war against the Owu in southern Yorubaland, which had broken out around the same time.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] This group then turned their attention to waging war with the Egba, a loose confederacy of towns that had been established by Yoruba migrants in the 13th century and were spread throughout the forested land between Ipara and Ibadan.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The group conquered and destroyed many of these towns, eventually settling in one of the villages that had not been completely destroyed, Ibadan, which they used as their headquarters for additional conquests.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] At least a handful of Egba groups had by this point joined the group of marauders, and they too were living at Ibadan.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Conflict between the various groups arose, and in one incident, an Egba chief named Lamodi shot an Ife chief named Ege to death with a pistol at a public meeting before himself being killed in the ensuing commotion.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Fearing Ife reprisal, most of the Egba population withdrew as a group to an encampment about 3 or 4 miles distant on the other side of the Ona River.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Here they enlisted Sodeke to be their leader and migrated to a hilly area known as Olumo Rock, where they established the town of Abeokuta around 1830 at what was then a small farming village.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Nevertheless, all accounts agree that in the 19th century, the Olumo Rock became a place of refuge for displaced Yoruba people during the Yoruba Revolutionary Wars, and from the Dahomey slave hunters.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] People were scattered throughout the landscape, taking shelter among the rocks surrounding the settlement.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Egba who established Abeokuta were soon joined by other Egba refugees and a substantial number of Owu who had escaped their captors.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] It became a busy metropolis and home to the majority of the Egba.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] However, the various groups of Egba did not fuse into a single community; rather, Abeokuta functioned more as a "federation of communities within a town wall than a community in its own right".
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Because Abeokuta was in a key location for the palm oil trade and because it was the so-called capital of the Egbas, Dahomey soon became hostile.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] In the 1851 Battle of Abeokuta, the Egba defeated King Gezo and the Dahomey incursion.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] They again beat back the Dahomey military in 1864.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The 1860s also saw problems arise with the Europeans, namely the British in Lagos, which led to the Egba first closing trade routes, followed by the expulsion of missionaries and traders in 1867.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Between 1877 and 1893 the Yoruba Civil Wars occurred, and Abeokuta opposed Ibadan, which led the king or *alake* of the Egba to sign an alliance with the British governor, Sir Gilbert Carter.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] This occurred in 1893, which formalized the Egba United Government based in Abẹokuta which became recognized by the United Kingdom.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] In 1914, the Egba lands were incorporated into the colony of Nigeria by the British, with Abeokuta as the provincial capital.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] In 1918, an uprising took place, the Adubi War, which was related to the levying of taxes and the policy of indirect rule by Sir Frederick Lugard, the British Governor-General.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] This was the only internal threat to British control of Nigeria during the course of the First World War.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Abeokuta Women's Revolt, led by the Abeokuta Women's Union (AWU), took place in the 1940s.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] It was a resistance movement against the imposition of unfair taxation by the Nigerian colonial government.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] In 1976, Abeokuta became the capital of the newly created Ogun State.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abeokuta is connected to nearby Lagos by a railway that was completed in 1899, with a length of 77 kilometres (48 mi).
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] In 2013, the Abeokuta flyover was constructed.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Since 2021 there is a standard gauge railway line Lagos-Ibadan, which stops at Abeokuta.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] For this a new railway building has been built in Abeokuta.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Tickets are bought by online booking only.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Roads connect it to Lagos as well as Ibadan, Ilaro, Shagamu, Iseyin, Sango Ota, and Ketou.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abeokuta's name already refers to several rock formations in the neighbourhood, especially Olumo Rock.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Visitors should be aware that the rock has a spiritual significance and respectful behaviour is therefore strongly recommended.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Olusegun Obasanjo Presidential Library is another tourist destination in Abeokuta.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Abeokuta was once surrounded by 29 kilometres (18 mi) of wall, and remnants of the historic wall still exist today.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] Ake, the traditional residence of the Alake, along with Centenary Hall (1930), are both in the Egba Alake's territory.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] There are secondary and primary schools and the University of Lagos Abeokuta Campus opened in 1984.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] This campus specializes in science, agriculture, and technology.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] This has since been changed to an independent full-fledged tertiary institution, Federal University of Agriculture, Abeokuta (FUNAAB) in 1988.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Green Legacy Resort is a large resort/hotel built by former president Olusegun Obasanjo and investors.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Olusegun Obasanjo Presidential Library (OOPL) is also located within the grounds of the resort.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The governor's office located at Oke-Mosan is also a notable building.
[src:akpeteshie/abeokuta] The Federal University of Agriculture, Abeokuta (FUNAAB), Federal College of Education, Osiele, are also notable locations in Abeokuta.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The capital's architecture reflects this history, ranging from 19th-century colonial architecture to modern skyscrapers and apartment blocks.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra is the Greater Accra Region's economic and administrative hub, and serves as the anchor of the larger Greater Accra Metropolitan Area (GAMA), which is inhabited by about 4 million people, making it the thirteenth-largest metropolitan area in Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 2020, the Globalization and World Cities Research Network think tank designated Accra as a "Gamma −" level global city, indicating a growing level of international influence and connectedness.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The word *Accra* is derived from the Akan word *Nkran* meaning "ants", a reference to anthills seen in the countryside around Accra.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The name specifically refers to soldier ants, and was applied to the town and people by the Twi speakers.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The name of Accra in the local Ga language is *Ga* or *Gaga*, the same name as that of the Ga people and a cognate with *Nkran*.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The word is sometimes rendered with the nasalised vowels as *Gã* or *Gãgã*.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Historian Carl Christian Reindorf confirmed this etymology, proposing a link between the martial qualities and migratory behaviour of the local ants and those of the Ga people.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The link between the ethnonym and ants was explicitly reflected in the recognition of anthills as sacred places.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Sometimes ringed by sacred fences (*aklabatsa*), the tall red mounds dotting Accra's hinterland were seen as microcosms of human community and as nodal points between the known world and the world of the dead.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Gas used the reference to the invasive species of dark-red swarming ants to connote the military prowess of the Gas and their ancient conquest of Guang speakers residing in the Accra Plains.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The name *Ga* is actually a cognate of the name *Akan*, one of the words in which [g] corresponds to [k] in Akan.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] *Ga* also gave its name to the Ga districts surrounding Accra.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The spelling *Accra* was given to *Nkran* by Europeans.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] By the 15th century, the kingdom of Accra ruled the area from the capital at Ayawaso.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Initially, Accra was not the most prominent trading centre; the trading hubs were the ports at Ada and Prampram, along with the inland centres of Dodowa and Akuse.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] A Portuguese fort was destroyed by the local inhabitants in 1576; trade afterwards was conducted on the beaches.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Dutch later built the nearby Fort Crèvecœur while the British and the Swedes built James Fort and Christiansborg castles, respectively, in the 17th century.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] By 1646 the kingdom was a regional power, bolstered by European trade.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] It depended on the goodwill of the rising Akwamu Kingdom, which controlled the trade routes in the interior.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] A dispute in 1646 escalated to war when Accra invaded Larteh.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] At the same time, Accra was weakened by a civil war.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 1677 Akwamuhene Ansa Sasraku, using the circumcision of a visiting Akwamu prince as pretext, attacked Accra.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] He sacked Ayawaso and beheaded the king, Okai Koi.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The king's son, Ofori, retreated to 'Small Accra', the town that had grown up under the walls of Fort Crèvecœur.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Ansa Sasraku's attempts to finish off the Accrans were defeated by the guns of the Danish Fort Christianborg.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Ofori and his people survived for years, until the Akwamu fomented a rebellion amongst the Danish garrison, and the fort was turned over to the Portuguese.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Ansa Sasraku returned in 1681, burning Osu town and Small Accra and chasing Ofori to exile in Fetu.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] As Akwamu continued to expand, strips of land east and west were added to the Accra province.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Britain gradually acquired the interests of all other countries beginning in 1851, when Denmark sold Christiansborg (which they had acquired from the Swedes) and their other forts to the British.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Netherlands was the last to sell out, in 1871.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 1873, after decades of tension between the British and Ashantis, the British captured Kumasi, destroying portions of the city.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The British then captured Accra in 1874, and in 1877, at the end of the second Anglo-Asante War, Accra replaced Cape Coast as the capital of the British Gold Coast.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This decision was made because Accra had a drier climate relative to Cape Coast.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Until this time, the settlement of Accra was confined between Ussher Fort to the east and the Korle Lagoon to the west.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Victoriaborg was formed in the 19th century as an exclusively European residential neighbourhood, located to the east of the city limits of the time.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The boundaries of Accra were further stretched in 1908, after a bubonic plague epidemic.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This expansion entailed the creation of a native-only neighbourhood, intended to accommodate members of the native population as a means of relieving congestion problems in the overcrowded city centre.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Adabraka was thus established to the north of the city.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 1918, the Grand Orange Lodge of Ghana was established in Accra to oversee and govern the local Ghanaian Orange Lodges.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Ghanaian Orange Order focus on evangelism, positive values and youth development.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] They have Orange parades in the city, such as the 12th of July parade.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] By the 1920s, transportation between Accra and the inland cities producing exportable commodities was enhanced.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This allowed cocoa to become Accra's largest export and allowed commerce to overtake government as the primary element in the city.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Among the achievements of Guggisberg was the building of a bridge across the Korle Lagoon in 1923, which increased settlement at Korle Bu, Korle Gonno and Chokor, to the west of the lagoon.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Guggisberg also oversaw the building of a hospital (Korle-Bu) and secondary school (Achimota).
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 1948, Ghana remained a colony of Great Britain following World War II.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The chief of Osu Alata, Nii Kobina Bonney III, had set up a boycott of European goods across the country due to the rise of prices for essential commodities.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] At the same time, veterans of the war were fighting for their benefits and promised pay.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] After Kwame Nkrumah became Ghana's first Prime Minister in 1957, he created his own plan for Accra's development.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Nkrumah proposed creating spaces to inspire pride and nationalism in his people and people throughout Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Parliament, Supreme Court of Ghana, Black Star Square and the Bank of Ghana are located in Accra.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The city is a transportation hub, home to Accra International Airport, and railway links to Tema, Sekondi-Takoradi and Kumasi.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra has become a location for national and international business conferences, such as the BarCamp Ghana series, organised by GhanaThink Foundation.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] As a coastal city, Accra is vulnerable to the impacts of climate change and sea level rise, with population growth putting increasing pressure on the coastal areas.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Drainage infrastructure is particularly at risk, which has implications for people's livelihoods, especially in informal settlements.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The administration of Accra occurs at two levels.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Strategic initiatives, such as the urban transportation project, are coordinated between district authorities.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Geographically, the areas west of Ring Road West, extending as far west as the saltponds and south of Graphic Road, are considered Accra West.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The period between 1960 and 1970 saw more rapid industrialization and expansion in Accra's manufacturing and commercial sectors.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This contributed to higher rural-urban migration to the city, and consequently a higher population growth rate.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] 56% of the population of Accra is under 24 years of age.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] 51% of the population are females, and the remaining 49% males.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This gives a males-to-females ratio of 1:1.04.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The greater number of females is a reflection of the nationwide trend, where the estimated ratio of males to females is 1:1.03.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 2008, the World Bank estimated that Accra's economy constituted around US$3 billion of Ghana's total gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra is a centre for manufacturing, marketing, finance, insurance, and transportation.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The road network in the Accra Metropolitan Area totals 1,117 kilometres (694 mi) in length.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] There are over 50,506 identified residential properties in Accra, and about 4,054 commercial/industrial/mixed properties, with a total rateable value of GH¢13,849,014.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The tertiary service sector is the city's largest, employing about 531,670 people.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The second-largest, the secondary sector, employs 22.34% of the labour force, or around 183,934 people.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] 12.2% of the city's workforce are reportedly unemployed, totalling around 114,198 people.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Pre-school comprises nursery and kindergarten.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 2001, there were 7,923 children (3,893 girls and 4,030 boys) in pre-schools in Accra.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 2010, the enrolment rate at Pre-school was 98%.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Primary school enrolment of girls is higher than that of boys.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 2010, the enrollment rate at primary school level was 95%.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 2010, the enrolment rate at Junior high school level was 95%.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The ratio of girls is higher at this level.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The transition rate between junior high and senior high school increased from 30% in 1990 to 50% in 2001.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The number of students grew by 23,102 between 1990 and 2005, an increase of about 2,310 a year, since 2010 the senior high school enrolment rate has been 95%.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Ghana International School (GIS), a private non-profit A-Level school founded in 1955 for children from ages 3–18, is located in Accra's Cantonments.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Abelemkpe is the home of Lincoln Community School, a private, non-profit International Baccalaureate (IB) school for students aged 3–18, established in 1968.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Mary's Senior High School, also referred to as "Merriez", is a girls' boarding school in Ghana; St.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The University of Ghana is located 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) north of the city centre at Legon.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] A number of other public and private universities and tertiary institutions have since been founded in Accra, some of which are listed below.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] As a growing city, Accra has a water supply and scarcity challenge.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Water access uses a patchwork of different delivery processes.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra as a growing city, with vehicles and other urban pollution sources, has an increasing amount of air pollution and plastic pollution.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra's urban ecosystem has been a site of dumping by international waste networks, with the Agbogbloshie suburb known for its e-waste recycling sites, and the Kantamanto Market as handling an overwhelming flow of used fast fashion from other parts of the world.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Both sites are sources of pollution and trash for other parts of the urban ecosystem.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Air pollution varies seasonally, and the average measure PM2.5 average concentration of 49.5 μg/m3.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Live monitoring of air pollution is done at three sites in the city of Accra.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] A 2021 review by the Environmental Protection Agency in Ghana found that the levels were exceeding national and international standards for health.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Plastic management is also an increasing challenge.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Use of plastic water bottles water sachets and other packaging for food safety, and use of plastic during events like COVID-19 have increased plastic pollution.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The beaches around Accra have plastic pollution, and surrounding fisheries are impacted by plastics.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Non-profit organizations have been formed to collect the plastic and an increasingly growing network of recyclers and informal waste recovery networks.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Activists and researchers largely attribute the issue to upstream use of plastics.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] There's been decongestion exercises carried out by successive mayors in the city to help solve the hawking menace, flood issues and ensure road safety in the city.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Growing population and construction within the city has been resulting in a reduction in Urban green space.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] A 2021 study of low income communities in the city found increasing concern and desire among these communities for urban green spaces for recreation and health.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] A 2018 study of greenspaces in the city, found the ones that do exist are important for mammal biodiversity in the city.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra is on the Atlantic coast and has not served as a port city since the 1950s.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Instead, the Port of Tema, about 29 km to the east along the Atlantic coast, was developed for deepwater shipping to and from Ghana as it can accommodate larger ships; the port opened in 1961.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra is connected by railway line to Kumasi and Takoradi.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] There is a suburban railway line from Accra Central Station to Tema.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra is served by Accra International Airport, which has civil and military uses.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Located 6 miles (9.7 kilometres) from downtown Accra, the airport handles all of the city's scheduled passenger services.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] There are plans to build a second airport to relieve the aviation pressure on the Accra International Airport.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This new airport will be located at Prampram in Accra and will be constructed by China Airport Civil Construction.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] This plan was still under review in 2020, as additional runways at Kotoka are in consideration as an alternative to a new international airport.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra has a taxi network and taxi ranks, and most taxis lack a meter system, so price negotiation is required between the passenger and driver.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Metered taxis operate in the city, and tend to be more expensive.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Taxis in Ghana are painted in two colours: the four bumpers fenders are yellow/orange, and the rest of the car is in a colour of the operator's choice.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] These taxis usually function on a shared ride model, where several passengers share one vehicle and the fare is calculated based on the distance traveled.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] More modern taxi services such as Uber, Taxify, and Yango have joined the market, providing a more advanced and comfortable alternative.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Some taxi drivers might charge extra for luggage or late-night trips while some also offer fixed prices and allow for advance bookings, offering a more reliable and secure option.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Tourism in Ghana accounted for 1,087,000 international tourist arrivals in 2011.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra is the Greater Accra region's tourist hub, sporting hotels, monuments, museums and nightclubs.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The city has three five-star hotels: the Labadi Beach Hotel, the La Palm Royal Beach Hotel and the Movenpick Ambassador Hotel.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Golden Tulip Hotel and Novotel Accra, located in Accra's central business district, are ranked four stars.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] There are three-star hotels, including the Hotel Wangara, Hotel Shangri-La and Erata Hotel, and budget hotels.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] The Accra International Conference Centre and other meeting facilities provide venues for conference tourism.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In 1994, Emmanuel Aboki Essien, a high-up member within the Grand Orange Lodge of Ghana, in Accra, was elected President of the Imperial Orange Council, the governing body of the worldwide Orange Order.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] He was the first African to hold this position, raising the profile of African Orange lodges within the fraternity.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Accra hold orange walks to celebrate historical events, such as the Battle of the Boyne.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] Its first documentary addressing the impacts of climate change premiered in Accra on 14 October 2022.
[src:akpeteshie/accra] In October 2022, Accra was named by the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) as World Book Capital for 2023.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Each region in Africa has developed its own distinctive culinary practices, shaped by local ingredients, colonial history and trade.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In **West Africa,** for example, dishes often feature rice, millet, and beans complemented by spicy stews made with fish, meat, and leafy greens.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The use of chili peppers, peanuts and palm oil is also widespread in this region.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] **Central African** cuisine on the other hand, tends to be simpler and relies heavily on starchy foods such as cassava and plantains, often served with sauces made with peanuts or vegetables.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In **East Africa**, particularly in countries like Kenya, Tanzania, and Uganda, the cuisine reflects a combination of native agricultural practices and influences from trade routes with India and the Middle East.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Staples such as maize, beans, and rice are commonly consumed along with dishes like Ugali (a maize-based porridge) and sukuma wiki (a dish made from collard greens).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The coastal areas of East Africa, particularly along the Swahili coast, feature seafood and curries seasoned with spices such as cardamom and cloves, a direct influence of Indian and Arab traders.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] **Southern African** cuisine also displays a blend of indigenous ingredients and colonial influences.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Dishes such as pap (a maize-based porridge) and biltong (a type of sausage) are popular in countries like South Africa, Botswana, and Namibia.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The cuisine is characterized by the use of game meat, maize, and beans, as well as European influences introduced during colonial times.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Traditionally, the various **cuisines of Africa** use a combination of plant-and seed-based ingredients, without having food imported.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In some parts of the continent, the traditional diet features an abundance of root tuber products.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Africa represents a rich history of adaptation, trade, and resourcefulness. while regional differences are pronounced, the use of local ingredients and traditional cooking techniques remains central to the continent's culinary identity.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Central Africa, East Africa, North Africa, Southern Africa and West Africa each have distinctive dishes, preparation techniques, and consumption modes.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The roots of native African cuisine goes back to thousands of years before the Bronze Age in Northeast Africa, when early civilizations began cultivating grains such as barley and wheat.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Part of North Africa is in the Fertile Crescent where settled agriculture was practiced by the Ancient Egyptians in this area.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Animals such as donkeys and sheep were also domesticated, starting the spread of agriculture to other parts of Africa, notably West Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Although most tribes still lived a simple hunter-gather diet.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Arab explorers- Leo Africanus and Ibn Battuta- provided accounts of African food which they encountered on their travels through sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Most European travelers stayed close to coastal areas until the 19th century.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Many of their diaries also recorded details on foods and crops.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Many staples were introduced later when Africa was colonized by the Europeans.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Foods that are now important parts of African cuisine such as maize and potatoes were not common until the 19th century.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The influence of African food on Caribbean, Brazilian, American Lowcountry cuisine, and Cajun cuisine from Louisiana is seen in rice dishes and green stews like the Afro-Caribbean efo, duckanoo and callaloo.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The vegetable okra, introduced from Africa, is used in classic Louisiana gumbos, and American rice growing in the Carolina.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Lowcountry was influenced by West African techniques of rice cultivation and many slaves hailed from the rice-growing regions of West Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Lowcountry cuisine is still known for its distinctive rice dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Central Africa expands from the Tibesti Mountains in the north to the vast rainforest basin of the Congo River, the highlands of Kivu and the savannah of Katanga.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] This region has received the culinary influence of the Swahilis (culture that evolved via the combination of Bantu, Yemeni, Omani and Indian cultures) during the trans-Saharan slave trade.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Swahili culinary influences can be found in dishes such as mandazi, pilaf rice, kachumbari, sambusa, and kuku paka.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Central African cuisine has also been influenced by the Portuguese, by way of the Kongo and Ndongo Kingdoms.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Salt fish was introduced following trade in the late 17th century, and the Kikongo term for salt fish, makayabu, comes from the Portuguese term bacalhau.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Portuguese culinary influence is especially prominent in Angola, Sao Tomé and Equatorial Guinea.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Central Africa has also been influenced by the cuisine of the East, West and Southern Africa regions because of their close proximity, e.g. babuté or bobotie is shared with the south, nyama choma with the east and sauce gombo with West Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In Central Africa, a variety of crops are grown, including yams, cassava, bananas and plantains, sweet potatoes, and cocoyams.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] These crops have become staples in the diet of many people in Central Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Fufu-like starchy foods are usually made from fermented cassava roots, but they can also be made with plantain, corn maize and yam.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Fufu is served buffet-style with grilled meat, fish, stews, greens and piment .
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A variety of local ingredients are used while preparing other dishes, like spinach stew cooked with tomato, peppers, chilies, onions, and peanut butter.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Eastern central Africa is also one of the few regions in Africa that uses potatoes as one of its main bases, since potatoes grow easily in the region.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Cassava plants are also consumed as cooked greens.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Groundnut (peanut) stew is also prepared, containing chicken, okra, ginger, and other spices.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Beef and chicken are favorite meat dishes, but game meat preparations containing crocodile, elephant, antelope and warthog meats are also served occasionally.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The cuisine of East Africa varies from area to area.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In the inland savannah, the traditional cuisine of cattle-keeping peoples is distinctive meaning that meat products are generally absent.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Cattle, sheep, pigs and goats were regarded as a form of currency and a store of wealth.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] They are not generally consumed as food.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In some areas, traditional East Africans consume the milk and blood of cattle, but rarely the meat.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Elsewhere, other Africans are farmers who grow a variety of grains and vegetables.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Maize (corn) is the basis of ugali', the local version of West and Central Africa's fufu.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Ugali is a starch dish eaten with meats or stews.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In Uganda, steamed green bananas called matoke provide the starch filler of many meals.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Around 1000 years ago, Omani and Yemeni merchants settled on the Swahili Coast.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Middle Eastern influences are especially reflected in the Swahili cuisine of the coast—steamed or cooked rice with spices in Persian style; saffron, cloves, cinnamon and several other spices; and pomegranate juice.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Several centuries later, the British and the Indians came, and both brought with them foods such as Indian spiced vegetable curries, lentil soups, chapattis and a variety of pickles which have influenced various local dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Some common ingredients used in this region include oranges, lemons, limes, chilies, capsicum peppers, maize, tomatoes, and strawberries.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In the Horn of Africa, the main traditional dishes in Eritrean cuisine and Ethiopian cuisine are tsebhis (stews) served with injera (flatbread made from teff, wheat, or sorghum) and hilbet (paste made from legumes, mainly lentils and fava beans).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian cuisine (especially in the northern half) are very similar, given the shared history of the two countries.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian food habits vary regionally.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In the highlands, injera is the staple diet and is eaten daily among the Tigrinya.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Injera is made out of teff, wheat, barley, sorghum or corn, and resembles a spongy, slightly sour pancake.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] When eating, diners generally share food from a large tray placed in the center of a low dining table.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Many injera are layered on this tray and topped with various spicy stews.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Diners then break into the section of injera in front of them, tearing off pieces and dipping them into the stews.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In the lowlands, the main dish is akelet, a porridge-like dish made from wheat flour dough.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A ladle is used to scoop out the top, which is filled with berbere and butter sauce and surrounded by milk or yoghurt.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A small piece of dough is broken and then used to scoop up the sauce.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The best known Ethiopian/Eritrean cuisine consists of various vegetable or meat side dishes and entrées, usually a wat, or thick stew, served atop injera, a large sourdough flatbread made of teff flour.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] One does not eat with utensils, but instead uses injera to scoop up the entrées and side dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Tihlo, prepared from roasted barley flour, is very popular in Amhara, Agame, and Awlaelo (Tigray).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Traditional Ethiopian cuisine employs no pork or shellfish of any kind, as they are forbidden in the Jewish and Ethiopian Orthodox Christian faiths.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] It is also very common to eat from the same dish in the center of the table with a group of people.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Somali cuisine varies from region to region and consists of an exotic mixture of diverse culinary influences.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] It is the product of Somalia's rich tradition of trade and commerce.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Despite the variety, there remains one thing that unites the various regional cuisines: all food is served halal.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] There are therefore no pork dishes, alcohol is not served, nothing that died on its own is eaten, and no blood is incorporated.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Varieties of bariis (rice), the most popular being basmati, usually serve as the main dish.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Spices like cumin, cardamom, cloves, cinnamon and sage are used to aromatize these different rice dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] During Ramadan, dinner is often served after Tarawih prayers, sometimes as late as 11 pm.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Xalwo (halwo) or halva is a popular confection served during special occasions such as Eid celebrations or wedding receptions.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] It is made from sugar, cornstarch, cardamom powder, nutmeg powder, and ghee.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Peanuts are also sometimes added to enhance texture and flavor.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] After meals, homes are traditionally perfumed using frankincense (lubaan) or incense (cuunsi), which is prepared inside an incense burner referred to as a dabqaad.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Food and nutrition security in East Africa (Rwanda, Burundi and South Sudan) is a significant issue.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The region has been plagued by drought, conflict and economic instability since the 1990s.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The current situation is characterized by low levels of food availability and high levels of malnutrition among young children.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The solution proposed for this problem is to increase local food production.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] This would be achieved by increasing agricultural productivity by improving soil fertility and water management, which will help farmers grow more crops per year.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] This will also help reduce poverty in the region by providing more employment opportunities for local people.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In a study of food loss and waste in North Africa, researchers found that the region was wasting about 30% of its food, which is likely to increase as the population continues to grow.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] This waste occurs for a variety of reasons, including lack of refrigeration and storage facilities.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] To solve this issue, the people had to get creative with new dishes and ways of storing food.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The more we looked, the more we found that people were using all parts of plants in some way—the leaves, stems, flowers, fruits and seeds.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] They also used every edible part of animals as well—from fat to bones for making broth or soup.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] North Africa lies along the Mediterranean Sea and encompasses within its fold several nations, including Morocco, Algeria, Libya, Tunisia, and Egypt.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The roots of North African cuisine can be traced back to the ancient empires of North Africa, particularly in Egypt, where many of the country's dishes and culinary traditions date back to African antiquity.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Over several centuries traders, travelers, invaders, migrants and immigrants all have influenced the cuisine of North Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Phoenicians of the 1st century brought sausages, while the Carthaginians introduced wheat and its by-product, semolina.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Berbers adapted semolina into couscous, one of the main staple foods.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Olives and olive oil were introduced before the arrival of the Romans.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] From the 7th century onwards, the Arabs introduced a variety of spices, like saffron, nutmeg, cinnamon, ginger and cloves, which contributed and influenced the culinary culture of North Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Ottoman Turks brought sweet pastries and other bakery products, and from the New World, North Africa got potatoes, tomatoes, zucchini and chili peppers.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In addition, two completely different dishes may also share the same name (for example, a tajine dish is a slow-cooked stew in Morocco, whereas the Tunisian tajine is a baked omelette/quiche-like dish).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] There are noticeable differences between the cooking styles of different nations, from the sophisticated, full-bodied flavors of Moroccan palace cookery to the fiery dishes of Tunisian cuisine and the humbler, simpler cuisines of Egypt and Algeria.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The cooking of the Southern Africa region (not to be confused with the country of South Africa) is sometimes called "rainbow cuisine", as the food in this region is a blend of many cultures: indigenous African societies, European, and Asian.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] To understand indigenous African cuisine, it is important to understand the various native peoples of southern Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The indigenous Africans of Southern Africa were roughly divided into two groups and several subgroups.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The largest group consisted of the Bantu-speakers, whose descendants today may identify themselves by various subgroup names such as Ndebele (northern and southern), Shona, Venda, Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Sotho, Tswana, Pedi and Tsonga.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] They arrived in the region around 2,000 years ago, bringing crop cultivation, animal husbandry, and iron toolmaking with them.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Hence the Bantu-speakers grew grain crops extensively and raised cattle, sheep and goats.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] They also grew and continue to grow pumpkins, beans, and leafy greens as vegetables.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A smaller group were the primeval residents of the region, the Khoisan, who some archaeologists believe had lived in the region for at least 10,000 years.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Many descendants of the Khoisan people have now been incorporated into the population of South Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Khoisan originally were hunter-gatherers (who came to be known as "San" by the Bantu-speakers and as "bushmen" by Europeans).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] After the arrival of the Bantu-speakers, however, some Khoisan adopted the Bantu-speakers' raising of cattle but did not grow crops.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] People were, in other words, defined to some extent by the kinds of food they ate.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Bantu-speakers ate dishes of grain, meat, milk and vegetables, as well as fermented grain and fermented milk products.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] While the Khoi-Khoi ate meat and milk and the San hunted wild animals and gathered wild tubers and vegetables.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In many ways, the daily food of native South African families can be traced to the indigenous foods that their native African ancestors ate.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Khoisan and Bantu traditionally ate roasted meat, and they also dried meat for later use.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The influence of their diet is reflected in the universal Southern African love of barbecue (generally called in South Africa by its Afrikaans name, a "braai") and biltong (dried preserved meat).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The traditional beer was ubiquitous in the southern African diet, and the fermentation added additional nutrients to the diet.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] It was a traditional obligation for any family to be able to offer a visitor copious amounts of beer.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Beer brewing was done by women, and the status of a housewife in pre-colonial southern Africa depended significantly on her skill at brewing delicious beer.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Milk was historically one of the most important components of the southern African diet.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Cattle were considered a man's most important possession.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In order to marry, a man had to compensate his prospective in-laws with a gift of cattle as a dowry for his bride.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A married man was expected to provide a generous supply of milk to his wife and children, along with meat whenever he slaughtered cattle, sheep or goats.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Because there was no refrigeration, milk was mostly soured into a kind of yogurt.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The young men of the family often took care of the cattle far away from the villages at "cattle posts," and they sent a steady stream of yogurt home on behalf of their fathers.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Today, many South Africans of African origin enjoy drinking sour milk products that are sold in the supermarket, comparable to American buttermilk, yogurt, and sour cream.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] On weekends they will have a "braai", and the meal usually consists of "pap and vleis", which is maize porridge and grilled meat as has historically been done in the region.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The basic ingredients include seafood, meat products (including wild game), poultry, as well as grains, fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Fruits include apples, grapes, mangoes, bananas, papayas, avocado, oranges, peaches and apricots.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Desserts may simply be fruit, but there are some more western-style puddings, such as malva pudding, reminiscent of sticky toffee pudding, which was inspired by both British cuisine and Dutch cuisine.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Meat products include lamb, and game like venison, ostrich, and impala.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The seafood includes crayfish, prawns, tuna, mussels, oysters, calamari, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] There are also several types of traditional and modern alcoholic beverages including many European-style beers.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A typical West African meal is made with starchy items and can contain meat, fish, as well as various spices and herbs.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A wide array of staples are eaten across the region, including fufu, banku, kenkey (originating from Ghana), foutou, couscous, tô, and garri, which are served alongside soups and stews.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Fufu is often made from starchy root vegetables such as yams, cocoyams, or cassava, and also from cereal grains like millet, sorghum or plantains.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The staple grain or starch varies between regions and ethnic groups, although corn has gained significant ground as it is cheap, swells to greater volumes and creates a beautiful white final product that is greatly desired.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Banku and kenkey are maize dough staples, and garri is made from dried grated cassavas.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Rice dishes are also widely eaten in the region, especially in the dry Sahel belt inland.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Examples of these include the Senegalese dish thieboudienne also known as benachin or Jollof rice, a pan-West African rice dish similar to Arab kabsah.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Seeds of Guinea pepper (Aframomum melegueta, also called grains of paradise or melegueta pepper), a native West African plant, were used as a spice and even reached Europe, through North African middlemen, during the Middle Ages.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Centuries before the influence of the Europeans, West Africans were trading with the Arab world and spices like cinnamon, cloves, and mint were not unknown, therefore becoming part of the local flavorings.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Centuries later, the Portuguese, French and British influenced the regional cuisines, but only to a limited extent.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques include roasting, baking, boiling, frying, mashing, and spicing.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] A range of sweets and savories are also prepared.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques of West Africa are changing.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In the past West Africans ate much less meat and used native oils (palm oil on the coast and shea butter in Sahelian regions).
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Baobob leaf and numerous local greens were everyday staples during certain times of the year.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Today the diet is much heavier in meats, salt, and fats.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Many dishes combine fish and meat, including dried and fermented fish.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Flaked and dried fish is often fried in oil, and sometimes cooked in sauce made with hot peppers, onions, tomatoes, various spices (such as soumbala), and water to prepare a highly flavored stew.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] In some areas beef and mutton are preferred, and goat meat is the dominant red meat.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Suya, a popular grilled spicy meat kebab flavored with peanuts and other spices, is sold by street vendors as a snack or evening meal and is typically made with beef or chicken.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] It is common to have a preponderance of seafood, which as earlier stated, is sometimes also mixed with other meat products.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Guinea fowl and chicken eggs are also preferred.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] With regard to beverages, water has a very strong ritual significance in many West African nations (particularly in dry areas) and water is often the first thing an African host will offer their guest.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Palm wine is also a common beverage made from the fermented sap of various types of palm trees and is usually sold in sweet (less-fermented, retaining more of the sap's sugar) or sour (fermented longer, making it stronger and less sweet) varieties.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The exact origins of Bitter Leaf soup appear to be unknown thought it is known to have been prepared and eaten for hundreds of years.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The dish traditionally consists of fish, meat (usually beef), bitter leaves, palm oil, and an array of spices and seasonings.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Shellfish such as shrimp or crayfish are often used alongside fish in the preparation of Bitter Leaf Soup.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] Due to the bitterness of bitter leaf, the bitter leaf is washed thoroughly to diminish the bitterness before being cooked with the rest of the ingredients.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] It is widely consumed in West Africa, especially Nigeria where it is associated with the Igbo people and referred to as Ofe Onugbu.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The Bitter Leaf itself is known scientifically as Vernonia amygdalina and is native to Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/african-cuisine] The bitter taste comes from the alkaloids contained within the plant.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] It is popular throughout West Africa, and goes by many names including **apio**, **ogoglo**, **ogogoro** (**Ogog'**), **VC10,** **Kill Me Quick**, **Efie Nipa, Kele, Kumepreko, Anferewoase, Apiatiti, Home Boy, Nana Drobo, One Touch** among others.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] It is also known as sapele water, kparaga, kai-kai, Sun gbalaja, egun inu igo meaning *The Masquerade in the Bottle*, push-me-push-you, and/or crim-kena, sonsé ("do you do it?" in Yoruba language).
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] In the Igbo language it is known as *Akpuru achia*.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Other Nigerian epithets include: *Udi Ogagan*, *Agbagba* Urhobo, as well *OHMS* (Our Home Made Stuff), *Iced Water*, *Push Me, I Push You* and *Craze man in the bottle*.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Ghanaian moonshine is referred to as akpeteshie.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] With British colonization of what became known as the Gold Coast, such local brewing was outlawed in the early 1930s.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Dotse about his life under British colonial rule: "Our contention was that the drink the white man brought is the same as ours.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The white men's contention was that ours was too strong...Before the white men came we were using akpeteshie.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] But when they came they banned it, probably because they wanted to make sales on their own liquor.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] When you had a visitor whom you knew very well, then you ordered that kpótomenui be brought.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The name "akpeteshie" was given to the drink with its prohibition: the word comes from the Ga language (*ape te shie*, the act of hiding) spoken in greater Accra and means *they are hiding*, referring to the secretive way in which non-European inhabitants were forced to consume the beverage.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Despite being outlawed, illicit spirits remained commonplace, with reports that even schoolboys were able to easily obtain akpeteshie through the 1930s.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Demand for akpeteshie and the profits to be made from its sale was enough to encourage the spread of sugar cane cultivation in the Anlo region of Ghana.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Distillation was legalized with decolonization and Ghanaian independence.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The first factory was established in the Volta Region, taking advantage of the area's supply of sugar cane plantations.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Ogogoro is distilled from the juice of Raffia palm trees.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] An incision is made in the trunk and a gourd placed outside it for collection, which is collected a day or two later.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] After extraction, the sap is boiled to form steam, which subsequently condenses and is collected for consumption.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is distilled from palm wine or sugarcane juice.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] This sweetened liquid or wine is first fermented in a large barrels, sometimes with the help of yeast.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] After this first stage of fermentation, fires are built under the barrels in order to bring the liquid to a boil and pass the resulting vapor through a copper pipe within cooling barrels, where it condenses and drips into sieved jars.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The boiled juice then undergoes a distillation.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The resulting spirit is between 40 and 50% alcohol by volume.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is not professionally bottled or sealed, but instead poured into unlabeled used bottles.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The spirit can be bought wholesale from a brewer or by the glass at boutiques and bars.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Although not professionally advertised, the drink is very popular.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] This is partially due to its price, which is lower than that of other professionally bottled or imported drinks.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Its relative cheapness makes it a drink associated more with the poor, but even those who can afford better quality are said to consume the spirit in secret.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The potency of the liquor heavily affects the bodily senses, providing a feeling likened to that of a knockout punch.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Practiced drinkers can be seen acknowledging receipt by blowing out air or pounding their chest.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] As drink and commodity, respectively, ogogoro carries substantial cultural and economic significance within Nigeria.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] It is an essential part of numerous religious and social ceremonies; Burutu (Ijaw) priests pour it onto the ground as offerings to contact their gods, while fathers of Nigerian brides use it as a libation by which they provide their official blessing to a wedding.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] The economic facets of ogogoro have been equally salient throughout recent Nigerian history.
[src:akpeteshie/akpeteshie] Many poor Nigerian families homebrew the drink as a means of economic subsistence, many of whom sell shots of it on city street corners.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] France, alcohol by volume is often referred to as **degrees Gay-Lussac** (after the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac), although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac convention uses the International Standard Atmosphere value for temperature, 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a change in volume.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass causes a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solutions above 24% causes a decrease in volume.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar solutions is called "partial molar volume".
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Water and ethanol are both polar solvents.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] When water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field of the other.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is usually found in non-polar mixtures.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Thus, alc/vol is not the same as volume fraction expressed as a percentage.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (commonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured separately.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] For example, to make 100 mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solution, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Whereas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50 mL of ethanol and 50 mL of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure less than 100 mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will contain a higher concentration of ethanol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The difference is not large, with the maximum difference being less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20%.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certified as a certain alcohol brand or label.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] For example, in the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada and European Union whisky is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Low-alcohol beers (<0.5) are considered in some countries such as Iran as permitted (halal) despite alcohol being banned.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typically the lowest commercially sold 0.05.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinking low-alcohol drinks.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The low concentration severely limits the rate of intake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Quickly drinking 1.5 L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% BAC in a study of German volunteers.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Healthy human kidneys can only excrete 0.8–1.0 L of water per hour, making water intoxication likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The process of ethanol fermentation will slow down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too concentrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for non-distilled alcoholic drinks.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is at 8–12%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14–18%, with speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Any higher would require distillation, producing liquor.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Details about typical amounts of alcohol contained in various beverages can be found in the articles about them.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] During the production of wine and beer, yeast is added to a sugary solution.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] During fermentation, the yeasts consume the sugars and produce alcohol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The density of sugar in water is greater than the density of alcohol in water.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] A hydrometer is used to measure the change in specific gravity (SG) of the solution before and after fermentation.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The volume of alcohol in the solution can then be estimated.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] There are a number of empirical formulae which brewers and winemakers use to estimate the alcohol content of the liquor made.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Specific gravity is the density of a liquid relative to that of water, i.e., if the density of the liquid is 1.05 times that of water, it has a specific gravity of 1.05.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] In UK brewing usage, it is customary to regard the reference value for water to be 1000, so the specific gravity of the same example beer would be quoted as 1050.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The formulas here assume that the former definition is used for specific gravity.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] During ethanol fermentation the yeast converts one mole of sugar into two moles of alcohol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] where 46.069 is the molar mass of ethanol and 180.156 is the molar mass of glucose and fructose.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] SG can be measured using an hydrometer and Brix can be calculated from SG.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] SG drop is how much the SG decreased during fermentation (at 20 degree C).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The factor 135 is most accurate in the center of the SG drop range of 0.000 to 0.179.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Advanced formula derived from Carl Balling empirical formulas.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The formula compensates for changes in SG with changes in alcohol concentration and for the fact that not all sugar is converted into alcohol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] where SG final is the specific gravity when fermentation ends, Plato start is the sugar by weight when fermentation begins, Plato final is the sugar by weight when fermentation ends.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Brix can be used instead of Plato as they are nearly identical.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol *proof*, which in the United States is twice the alcohol-by-volume (alc/vol) number.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] This may lead to confusion over similar products bought in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] For example, Stroh rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as *Stroh 80* when sold in Europe, but is named *Stroh 160* when sold in the United States.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] In the United Kingdom, proof is 1.75 times the number (expressed as a percentage).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] For example, 40% alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] However, since 1980, alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcohol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] In the United States, Arkansas, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to **alcohol by weight** (**ABW**), expressed as a percentage of total mass.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than the ABW.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alcohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcohol, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with the density of alcohol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-by-volume] However, because of the miscibility of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather depends upon the concentration of alcohol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The measurement of alcohol content and the statement of content on bottles of alcoholic beverages is regulated by law in many countries.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] In 1972, Canada phased out the use of "proof"; in 1973, the European Union followed suit; and the United Kingdom, where the concept originated, started using ABV instead in 1980.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The United States Code mandates the use of ABV, but permits proof to be used also.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The degree symbol (°) is sometimes used to indicate alcohol proof, either alone (e.g.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] 10°) or after a space and joined to the letter P as a unit name (e.g.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The term *proof* dates back to 16th century England, when spirits were taxed at different rates depending on their alcohol content.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Similar terminology and methodology spread to other nations as spirit distillation, and taxation, became common.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] In England, spirits were originally tested with a basic "burn-or-no-burn" test, in which an alcohol-containing liquid that would ignite was said to be "above proof", and one which would not was said to be "under proof".
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] A liquid just alcoholic enough to maintain combustion was defined as 100 proof and was the basis for taxation.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Because the flash point of alcohol is highly dependent on temperature, 100 proof defined this way ranges from 20% at 36 °C (97 °F) to 96% at 13 °C (55 °F) alcohol by *weight* (ABW); at 24 °C (75 °F) 100 proof would be 50% AB*W*.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Another early method for testing liquor's alcohol content was the "gunpowder method".
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Gunpowder was soaked in a spirit, and if the gunpowder could still burn, the spirit was rated above proof.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] This test relies on the fact that potassium nitrate (a chemical in gunpowder) is significantly more soluble in water than in alcohol.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] While less influenced by temperature than the simpler burn-or-no-burn test, gunpowder tests also lacked true reproducibility.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Factors including the grain size of gunpowder and the time it sat in the spirit impact the dissolution of potassium nitrate and therefore what would be defined as 100 proof.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] However, the gunpowder method is significantly less variable than the burn-or-no-burn method, and 100 proof defined by it is traditionally defined as 57.15% ABV.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] By the end of the 17th century, England had introduced tests based on specific gravity for defining proof.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] However, it was not until 1816 that a legal standard based on specific density was defined in England.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] 100 proof was defined as a spirit with 12⁄13 the specific gravity of pure water at the same temperature.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] From the 19th century until 1 January 1980, the UK officially measured alcohol content by proof spirit, defined as spirit with a gravity of 12⁄13 that of water, or 923 kg/m3 (1,556 lb/cu yd), and equivalent to 57.15% ABV.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] This led to the approximation that 100-proof spirit has an ABV of 4⁄7.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] From this, it follows that to convert the ABV expressed as a percentage to degrees proof, it is only necessary to multiply the ABV by 7⁄4.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Thus pure 100% alcohol will have 100×(7⁄4) = 175 proof, and a spirit containing 40% ABV will have 40×(7⁄4) = 70 proof.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The proof system in the United States was established around 1848 and was based on percent alcohol rather than specific gravity.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Fifty percent alcohol by volume was defined as 100 proof.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] This is different from 50% volume fraction (expressed as a percentage); the latter does not take into account change in volume on mixing, whereas the former does.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] To make 50% ABV from pure alcohol, one would take 50 parts of alcohol and dilute to 100 parts of solution with water, all the while mixing the solution.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] To make 50% alcohol by volume fraction, one would take 50 parts alcohol and 50 parts water, measured separately, and then mix them together.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The resulting volume will not be 100 parts but between 96 and 97 parts, since the smaller water molecules can take up some of the space between the larger alcohol molecules (see volume change).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The use of proof as a measure of alcohol content is now mostly linguistic and historical.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Today, liquor is sold in most locations with labels that state its percentage alcohol by volume.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The European Union (EU) follows recommendations of the International Organization of Legal Metrology (OIML).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] 22 (1973) provides standards for measuring alcohol strength by volume and by mass.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] A preference for one method over the other is not stated in the document, but if alcohol strength by volume is used, it must be expressed as a percentage of total volume at a temperature of 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The document does not address alcohol proof or the labeling of bottles.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] On 1 January 1980, Britain adopted the ABV system of measurement prescribed by the European Union, of which it was then a member.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The OIML recommendation for ABV used by the EU states the alcohol by volume in a mixture containing alcohol as a percentage of the total volume of the mixture at a temperature of 293.15 K [20.00 °C; 68.00 °F].
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] It replaced the Sikes hydrometer method of measuring the proof of spirits, which had been used in Britain for over 160 years.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] In the United States, alcohol content is legally mandated to be specified as an ABV percentage.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] For bottled spirits over 100 ml (3.5 imp fl oz; 3.4 US fl oz) containing no solids, actual alcohol content is allowed to vary by up to 0.15% of the ABV stated on the label.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] By contrast, bottled spirits which are less than 100 ml (as well as those which otherwise contain solids) may vary by up to 0.25%.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Proof (the term *degrees proof* is not used), defined as being twice the percentage of alcohol by volume, may be optionally stated in conjunction with the ABV.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] For example, whisky may be labeled as 50% ABV and as 100 proof; 86-proof whisky contains 43% ABV.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The most typical bottling proof for spirits in the United States is 80 US proof, and there is special legal recognition of 100-proof spirits in the bottled in bond category defined since 1897.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The Code of Federal Regulations requires that liquor labels state the percentage of ABV at a temperature of 60 °F (16 °C).
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] The regulation permits, but does not require, a statement of the proof, provided that it is printed close to the ABV number.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] In practice, proof levels continue to be stated on nearly all spirits labels in the United States, and are more commonly used than ABV when describing spirits in journalism and informal settings.
[src:akpeteshie/alcohol-proof] Beverages were labelled by alcohol proof in Canada until 1972, then replaced by ABV.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algerian cuisine offers a variety of dishes depending on the region and the season, but vegetables and cereals remain at its core.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Most Algerian dishes are centered around breads, meats (lamb, beef or poultry), olive oil, vegetables, and fresh herbs.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Vegetables are often used for salads, soups, tajines, couscous, and sauce-based dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Of all the Algerian traditional dishes available, the most famous one is Algerian couscous, recognized as a national dish.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Pork consumption is forbidden to Muslims in Algeria, in accordance with Islamic dietary laws.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algeria, like other Maghreb countries, produces a large range of Mediterranean fruits and vegetables and even some tropical ones.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Mediterranean seafood and fish are also eaten.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algerians consume a significant amount of meat, and it is found in almost every dish.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Mutton is the most eaten meat in the country.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Poultry and beef are also used; more uncommon types of meat such as game birds and venison are considered delicacies.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] In the south, dromedary (camel meat) is also eaten.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Meat could traditionally be dried in regions such as Kabylia as a way to preserve the meat for long amounts of time.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Vegetables are often used in stews (*tagine*/*jwaz*/*djwizza*) and soups (*chorba*/*harira*/*jari*), or simply fried or steamed.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Sardines, hake, shrimp, octopus, tuna and cod are the main items of seafood commonly eaten in Algerian cuisine, mostly in stews or fried.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Many spices are used in Algerian cuisine, including different kinds of dried red chili pepper, caraway, cumin, cinnamon, turmeric, ginger, paprika, coriander, saffron, mace, cloves, fennel, anise, nutmeg, cayenne pepper, fenugreek, and black pepper.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Some spice mixes are also traditional to the North African region, such as *ras el hanout*, which can be made of up to 27 spices.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] *Hror* is a spice mix typical of Algerian cuisine mainly made from galangal, cubeb, nutmeg and cinnamon, but recipes may include more spices and herbs such as liquorice or pellitory.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Some small starters can be eaten either before the main dish (traditionally done during Ramadan).
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] These starters are generally soups (most famously *chorba*) but also include *kemia*, some small dish of offal (such as liver or kidneys) or carrots with cumin (*zorodiyya mcharmla*).
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] A common and one of the most favorite dishes of Algerian cuisine is couscous.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The semolina is traditionally made from wheat but can also be made with barley.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The grains can also be fermented to make *el Hammoun* couscous.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The dish can be prepared in many ways, generally with a sauce with beef or lamb and zucchini, carrots, chickpeas and green bean, chicken, lentils and black-eyed pea.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Couscous can also be consumed in a *masfouf* (or thameqfoult in Kabyle), a dry version with no sauce and vegetables such as broad beans, peas or also with raisins and dates, traditionally along with fermented milk.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Several pasta dishes can be found in the traditional Algerian cuisine: *rechta*, *chakhchoukha*, *berkoukes*, *tikourbabine* (also called *asban*), *Aftir oukessoul* *tlitli* or *trida*.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] These traditional pasta dishes are prepared in a red stew, with the exception of rechta which is generally made in a white stew in Algeria, with meat and vegetables.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Vegetarian dishes in Algeria are also a main part of the diet with *karantita* (chickpeas flan), *tbikha* (vegetable stew), shakshouka (sort of ratatouille, often cooked with eggs), *zaalouka* (ratatouille of eggplants and tomatoes mainly, served hot or cold).
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] These dishes are often consumed with bread.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algeria has four well-known traditional soups consumed throughout the country: *chorba frik* (which is also cooked with *kadaif* in some regions in place of the *frik*), *harira*, *djari* and *tchicha*.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] These traditional Algerian soups are served at the beginning of the meal as an entree and are mainly prepared from lamb, mutton or chicken, chickpeas, tomatoes, vermicelli, wheat, spices and different vegetables and legumes.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] These varied soups are the most popular during the holy month of Ramadan.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The *gaspacho oranais* is an Algerian version of a Manchego dish.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The *chorba* has another variant, the *chorba bida* (white chorba) which is cooked with chicken, *kadaif*, chickpeas and pasley without any tomato.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] It is traditionally eaten with a squeeze of lemon juice.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Typically, seasonal fruits are served as a dessert at the end of meals.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] These fruits include watermelon, loquat, grape, pomegranate or dates (which can also be served at the beginning of the meal).
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Common pastries include *dziriyat*, *garn ghzal* (similar to gazelle ankles), *baqlawa*, *mhancha*, *bradj*, *makroudh*, *kalb elouz,* *zlabiya*, and *griwech* (a deep-fried pretzel-shaped dough, soaked in honey and sprinkled with sesame seeds).
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Many pastries are prepared for special occasions, such as Eid-al-Fitr and weddings.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] For example, the mouna was traditionally served by newlywed women to other women during their traditional *hammam*.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The *tamina* is a kind of paste made with semolina, butter, *hror* or other spices and honey, usually served after a woman gave birth.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] M'semen, *sfenj* or baghrir are generally served with tea and can be topped with honey, jam or even olive oil and sugar.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Creponne, a sorbet which originated in Oran, is a specialty in Algeria.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Other desserts and cakes such as sfenj and kroki mchawcha are also commonly eaten.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Green tea with mint is generally drunk in the afternoon and during ceremonies with pastries.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] When fresh mint is not available, dried leaves can be used instead.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Geranium tea can also be prepared with geranium leaves instead of mint.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Generally, tea is prepared with green tea leaves, either of the gunpowder blend or *chaara sandook* (green tea with a lighter taste than the bitter gunpowder blend).
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algerians are heavy coffee consumers; thick espresso and black coffee are very popular, Algerian breakfast consists of a latte coffee with croissants or bread with butter or any Algerian sweets like Algerian baklawa, msemen or baghrir topped with honey or jam.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Mazagran, which is said to be the “original iced coffee”, originated in Algeria; it is a cold sweetened coffee drink.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Fruit juice and soft drinks, called *gazouz*, are common and often drunk daily.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The most famous Algerian soda is Hamoud Boualem, an Algerian soft drink manufacturer that makes drinks popular in Algeria and exports them abroad, primarily for consumption by Algerian emigrants.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] It is one of the country's oldest companies, having been founded in 1878.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Their products include sodas like "Selecto," "Hamoud," and "Slim", each in multiple flavors, as well as syrups in different flavors.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algeria previously produced a large quantity of Algerian wine during the French colonization but production has decreased since its independence.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Alcohol consumption is frowned upon in Algeria but is not legally prohibited, which does not prevent the winegrower from producing a wide variety of wines mainly from the slopes of Mascara, Médéa and Tlemcen.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algerian cuisine is characterized by its use of flavorful spices and herbs, and a variety of sauces play an important role in many dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Two popular Algerian sauces are harissa and dersa.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Harissa is a spicy chili paste that is made from dried chili peppers, garlic, olive oil, and various spices such as caraway and coriander.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] It is often used as a condiment to add heat and flavor to stews, soups, and grilled meats.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Harissa can also be used as a marinade for meat or seafood.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Dersa is a milder sauce that is made from garlic, lemon juice, olive oil, and a variety of herbs such as parsley, cilantro, and mint.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] It is often used as a dipping sauce for bread, vegetables, or grilled meats.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Dersa can also be used as a marinade or dressing for salads.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Zaalouk: a traditional dip used in Algeria made from eggplant, tomatoes, garlic, and spices, typically served as an appetizer or side dish.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Chermoula, a marinade made from garlic, cilantro, lemon juice, and spices, commonly used to flavor seafood and meat dishes.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Toum: a garlic sauce made from garlic, lemon juice, and olive oil, similar to aioli, often served with grilled meats or as a dip.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Shakshuka sauce: a spicy tomato sauce made with onions, peppers, and a variety of spices, often used in the popular egg dish of the same name.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Hmiss is another popular condiment in Algerian cuisine.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] It is a spicy tomato sauce made from roasted red peppers, tomatoes, garlic, olive oil, and chili peppers.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Hmiss is usually served as a dip or spread with bread or grilled meat, and it can also be used as a topping for sandwiches or pizza.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] The roasted red peppers give hmiss a smoky flavor, while the chili peppers add heat, making it a flavorful and spicy condiment.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] In some parts of Algeria, hmiss is also made with the addition of spices such as cumin and paprika, giving it a unique regional variation.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Between 1976 and 1984, the average Algerian family spent around 56% of their income on food and drink, of which 10% was spent on bread and other cereal products.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Bread is thought to contain God's blessing, *baraka*.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] It is traditionally seen as a symbol of life and functions in rituals symbolic of life, fertility and abundance.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] French *baguettes*—white, leavened wheat flour.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Bought at bakery or street vendor, but never made at home due to access to mills powered by electricity.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Power shortages prevent consumption of this bread, and often Algerians turn to home-made breads that are milled by women's hands.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] French bread tends to be given more value in terms of taste and quality in that it was commonly associated to being more suitable to higher standards.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] However, the white inner parts of a baguette are thought to be unhealthy and will regularly be thrown away, and the bread is frequently associated with constipation.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Algerian breads, on the other hand, are considered more nutritive, rich and tasteful and seldom go to waste.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Because French breads harden over night or become chewy when put away in plastic bags, it is hard to find usage for them, so they are thrown away with more frequency than Algerian breads that can be reheated or reutilized as edible food utensils or even bird feed.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] In the context of rituals, only Algerian bread is thought suitable.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] Breads offered to guests should be homemade, as it signifies the essence, intimacy, and qualities of the family.
[src:akpeteshie/algerian-cuisine] In daily practices, it is also a sign of wealth and affluence if one has extra bread at the table, and making bread at home can be considered a sign of familial economic independence.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Currently, *Allanblackia* seeds are harvested in the wild to produce the oil, but these producers cannot produce enough oil to meet market demand.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Finding sustainable ways to increase production could bring many social, environmental, and economic benefits to the communities which produce *Allanblackia*.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] To ensure increased production is sustainable and benefits the communities growing the trees, a number of organizations have collaborated to develop a set of standards and methods as guidelines for increasing *Allanblackia* production.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Other organizations are working to establish tree nurseries and other sustainable means of domesticating *Allanblackia*.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Allanblackia oil is an edible vegetable oil derived from the seeds from the fruits of *Allanblackia* trees.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] This is an evergreen tree producing big brown fruits.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Inside those fruits are the seeds that contain the allanblackia oil.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia*, which belongs to the family Clusiaceae, consists of nine (possibly ten) tree species, all restricted to Africa.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] All members of the genus are dioecious (having separate male and female trees).
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] There are nine published species of *Allanblackia*, mostly very similar to each other.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] *Allanblackia* trees are commonly found in the wet tropical rain belt of West, Central and East Africa (from Sierra Leone to Tanzania).
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] They grow primarily in tropical rainforests, but can also be found on cultivated farmland areas.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] These species occur in moist low-land areas (*A. parviflora*, *A. floribunda*) or upland rain forests (*A. stuhlmannii*).
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia* was named in honour of the botanist Allan Black.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] He was the first curator of Kew Gardens and was responsible for the private collection of Charles Darwin.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Very respected amongst his peers, he died at a young age aboard ship off the Cocos Islands in the Bay of Bengal and the genus *Allanblackia* was named in his memory.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The name of *Allanblackia* trees used by the indigenous people in Tanzania is actually *msambu* or *mkimbo* in Swahili or sometimes *mkani* (*mkanyi*, *mkany*) in local languages.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] In Nigeria area of River State the local name used is *obiobo obo*.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] A key characteristic is that the fatty acids are organized into a two main triglycerides.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] These are called 1,3-distearoyl-2-oleoyl-glycerol (abbreviated as SOS at an average level of 69%) and 1,2-dioleoyl-3-stearoyl-sn-glycerol (abbreviated as sn-SOO at an average level of 23%).
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] This simple triglyceride composition provides *Allanblackia* seed oil with very steep melting behavior.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] This composition makes it useful for making food products such as margarine, without any further modification like fractionation of fractional crystallization.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Specific physical characteristics of SOS-SOO mixtures, like fat crystallization aspects, have extensively been investigated in model systems.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The volumes of Allanblackia seeds, and hence seed oil, produced until now very low.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The volume of allanblackia seed oil is in the range of 100 metric tonnes per annum only.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] These volumes are generated by wild-harvesting mainly done by collectors in Tanzania.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] When initial studies on the potential of wild-harvesting were done in the early 2000s, the expectations were very high predicting annual production of up to 40,000 tonnes of seeds.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] In reality only a few tonnes of seeds were harvested in the first year as the number of wild Allanblackia trees that could actually be harvested had severely been overestimated.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Through the plantation of the tree with local farmers in Tanzania, Ghana and Nigeria, the production volumes are expected to increase in the coming decade, once these trees are old enough to starting producing fruits and big enough to carry more of the large fruit pods.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Increasing the volumes obviously must be done sustainably and hence socio-economic and environmental aspects are being looked at.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] For example, the value of Allanblackia as a new cash (annual) crop for Africa means training of local communities not to cut Allanblackia trees for use as timber and firewood.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] But doing so is also a means of helping to conserve local biodiversity.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The Union for Ethical Biotrade (UEBT) has developed a standard and a verification framework against which the sustainability of the Allanblackia supply chain can be audited and approved.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] UEBT is a member of the International Social and Environmental Accreditation and Labelling Alliance, which promotes sustainability standards.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Wild harvesting as a production method is limited because there are not enough trees to satisfy demand and Allanblackia's flowering and fruiting behavior is erratic.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Since 2006, Novel Development Tanzania has been involved in a domestication program together with the World Agroforestry Centre to domesticate the species using participatory tree domestication approach.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The program includes community sensitization, exploration, participatory selections of superior mother trees, conservation in field gene banks, development of agroforestry systems with Allanblackia and market development.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Secondly, the program consists of developing asexual and sexual propagation protocols, which are necessary to overcome challenges in multiplication such as seed dormancy, long juvenile phase and high variability of desired traits.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The domestication program of Allanblackia through public-private partnership and participatory tree domestication could serve as a model for domestication of other underutilized African tree species of high economic potential.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] In Tanzania the use of allanblackia seed oil goes back almost a century.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] It has been reported that during the First World War allanblackia oil was already tested as a cocoa butter alternative.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Also in the seventies the such application was again explored in Europe.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] However the application never hit the market because larger volumes of the oil were simply not available due to the lack of an organized supply chain.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Nowadays there is still in hardly any local use of Allanblackia seed oil as people prefer use of easily available liquid oils and cheap industrial soaps.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The allanblackia tree has predominantly been used for timber in the last decades and hence the number of trees has significantly reduced .
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Most of the allanblackia trees nowadays remaining in the wild are growing in the East Usambara Mountains which provides the right climate for this tree.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] As a result, even today the volumes of oil available from wild-harvesting are still very small.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] The major application potential identified today is in the use as a structuring fat to produce low-trans margarines and dairy cream alternatives, and as cocoa butter equivalent in confectionery applications.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] In the European Union as of December 2014, all different types of vegetable oils will be listed on the ingredient label of food products using those ingredients.
[src:akpeteshie/allanblackia-oil] Recently Allanblackia seed oil was introduced in margarine and can be found as such on the product ingredient list.
